<section><div class=3D"wrap cav">
  <p class=3D"eyebrow">Chapter 4 =C2=B7 Read this before quoting it</p>
  <h2>What this does =E2=80=94 and doesn't =E2=80=94 show</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>NDVI measures greenness, not wellbeing.</strong> A soybean =
megafarm and an old-growth forest can green the same pixel; greening is not=
 automatically good news, and browning is not automatically neglect.</li>
    <li><strong>Much of the greening is agriculture and CO=E2=82=82.</stron=
g> Intensified farming and CO=E2=82=82 fertilization drive large shares of =
the global signal =E2=80=94 the divide partly reflects who can afford inten=
sification.</li>
    <li><strong>Country means hide within-country inequality.</strong> A na=
tional average can mask booming irrigated regions next to degrading dryland=
s.</li>
    <li><strong>Income groups are coarse.</strong> World Bank classificatio=
ns shift over time and bundle very different economies; they're a lens, not=
 a verdict.</li>
    <li><strong>Correlation, not causation.</strong> This explorer document=
s a pattern across income groups; it does not identify the mechanism behind=
 it.</li>
  </ul>
</div></section>

<section style=3D"padding-top:30px"><div class=3D"wrap meth">
  <p class=3D"eyebrow">Methods &amp; data</p>
  <h2>How it's built</h2>
  <p><strong>Signal.</strong> Country-level annual mean NDVI from the MODIS=
 vegetation-index record (2000=E2=80=932024). For every country, the series=
 is converted to percent change against that country's own 2000=E2=80=93200=
5 mean, so each place is compared with itself before places are compared wi=
th each other.</p>
  <p><strong>Groups.</strong> Countries are grouped by World Bank income cl=
assification; group lines are unweighted means across member countries, so =
small countries count equally and giants don't dominate the story.</p>
  <p><strong>This page.</strong> A single static site: globe rendered with =
globe.gl (Natural Earth 110m boundaries), chart hand-drawn in SVG, no build=
 step. Data lives inline and is regenerated from a CSV export by <code>prep=
are_data.py</code>.</p>
</div></section>

